I'm currently enrolled in CS50 Python and plan to take CS50 SQL next. After that, I wanted to know if Google's Advanced Data Analytics course is a good choice for someone like me who doesn't have a fundamental understanding of data science and statistics. I'm also interested in statistical learning, but I'm not sure how to go about it since it's currently in R on edX. I did find a book in Python for it, though.  I also have an interest in computer vision applications in the field of earth observation and machine learning for spatial data patterns. author: @geerliglecluse5297
text: Even if it won't be as good as advertised by Microsoft, all the new possibilities provided by Co-pilot, Chat GPT/Bing and Python in Excel are still very exciting. Together, these are the single biggest upgrade to Microsoft Office since its very introduction 25 years or so ago. Yes, it will change work. Yet at the same time fears that lots of jobs will disappear are likely overblown. We can't turn back the clock, and time doesn't stand still either. Business is competitive and so is work to some extent. Level up, figure out how it works and reap the benefits. Most of the new features will result in increased productivity by reducing the amount of donkey work. The resulting productivity improvements are the single most important long(er) term driver for healthy economic growth and prosperity for all of us, provided we're willing to change and level up.
